  "footnotes": [
    "Khmer Empire (802–c.1431): founded by Jayavarman II, it became the largest pre-modern state in mainland Southeast Asia; Angkor at its peak had a population exceeding 750,000; Jayavarman VII (1181–1218) built Angkor Thom and the Bayon; Thai pressure and ecological collapse (water management failure) contributed to its decline and the abandonment of Angkor",
    "Sukhothai (c.1238–1438): traditionally considered the first Thai kingdom; King Ramkhamhaeng allegedly invented the Thai script (1292); its political model emphasized paternalistic kingship (pho khun); it was absorbed by the rising Ayutthaya kingdom in 1438",
    "Ayutthaya (1351–1767): the dominant Siamese kingdom for four centuries, rivaling Ming China in diplomatic reach; it controlled much of mainland Southeast Asia; the Burmese sacked and destroyed Ayutthaya in 1767, one of the most devastating events in Thai history; Taksin rebuilt from Thonburi, then the Chakri dynasty moved to Bangkok",
    "Lan Xang (1353–1707): the 'Kingdom of a Million Elephants', founded by Fa Ngum with Khmer backing; at its peak it controlled most of modern Laos and parts of Thailand's Isan region; internal succession disputes split it into the three kingdoms of Luang Prabang, Vientiane, and Champasak in 1707, all eventually falling under Siamese suzerainty",
    "Siam's independence: Thailand (Siam) is the only Southeast Asian country never colonized by a European power; Rama IV (Mongkut) and Rama V (Chulalongkorn) pursued modernization and played Britain and France against each other; the price was ceding Lao territories to France (1893) and Malay territories to Britain (1909)",
    "Khmer Rouge (1975–1979): Pol Pot's regime emptied cities, abolished money, and attempted agrarian revolution; an estimated 1.5–2 million Cambodians (25% of the population) died from execution, starvation, and forced labor; Vietnam invaded in 1979 and installed a client government; the Khmer Rouge fought on until final collapse in 1999",
    "Lao People's Democratic Republic (1975–): the Pathet Lao abolished the monarchy and established a one-party communist state closely aligned with Vietnam; Laos remains one of the few communist states worldwide; economic reforms since 1986 have opened it to foreign investment while maintaining political control"
  ]
}
